column11: This question will be resolved using the daily closing price of the market of interest reported by Google Finance. Question will be suspended the day before the date of interest and resolved the day after the date of interest.

Based on general news and GJP consensus.

The lowest closing in the last 52 weeks was, 11,425.14. As of Today Oct 20th it is sitting 12,990. Out of the top 10 weighted countries that contribute to the performance of DAX, only 3 show signs of poor performance/downward trend. while the other 7 (in the top 10) are performing well. An unforeseen catastrophe that would impact all companies in the DAX would need to occur before the 31st of October to make it dip below 12,213.98. As such it is highly likely that DAX will close above 12,213.98 on Oct 31, 2017.
Notwithstanding that a crash in the S&P could have knockover effects, it is not guaranteed to occur in the next couple of weeks.
I am 'extremizing' my prior forecast by prorating the low probability bins to the other bin.

Versus current level, 12,214 represents a ~6% decline within a 14-trading-day timespan, while the DAX has been running ~11% annualized stdev over the last 12 months. Even using a more conservative stdev of 15%, this equates to less than 0.8% stdev over the 14-day window (calculated as (1.15^(14/252))-1). Thus, a 6% decline would represent a 7+ stdev event if the tails of returns distributions weren't so fat, so adjusted the probability for both downside scenarios upward slightly.
